metadata.description:
"I shall be telling this with a sigh

Two roads diverged in a wood, and I—
I took the one less traveled by,
And that has made all the difference."

- Robert Frost, The Road Not Taken

metadata.name: BRUTALIST MOVEMENT #192
metadata.description:
Inspired and fascinated by Brutalism, Modernism and Bauhaus, I've started to explore the deeper connections of architecture using pixel art in a clean, minimalistic and unique way.

The BRUTALIST MOVEMENT project represents the next step in this process. It's an animated generative experiment that focuses on finding the simplest and fewest components that - when generated randomly - always create structures resembling buildings: from small modern houses through industrial facilities to gigantic brutalist monuments.

This resulted in 4 main components: Base, Extension, Gap and Window. These entities are used randomly to create Blocks that form the final structure. 
The whole process is also strictly accompanied by 4 distinct components to hold colors and to be set by randomly chosen palettes: Sky, Sun, Shadow, Window.

Features consist of a mixture of the above components.

The project is animated to show how the buildings come to life. It's also a nice way to show what's going on in the background, because from time to time a bigger block would surely hide interesting smaller ones :) 

Press these keys:
's' - to download a larger resolution PNG
'n' - to shuffle through the 'depth' of Blocks, aka placing them from front to back and vice versa. This is a nice feature to show structures hidden by others and also a cool way to create iterations inside the iteration - sub-iterations - we can say :)
'r' - to reset the Blocks' depths to default

Please note:
Everything you see is generated, animated and drawn real-time. No layered transparent PNGs, PFP or similar!

Have fun and inspiration!


@cloudnoise © 2022

☁︎

Created with P5.js library.

metadata.name: possibleScapes #2
metadata.description:
When memory, photography and code interrelate.

The animated images, accumulations of other images, reveal themselves as fragments of memory.

Like old slides from a time gone by, logs bring possibleScapes that connect differently with each of the spectators.

Working together as a continuous system of gears, the algorithm is associated with the image bank, creating the most diverse interferences, revealing unique possibilities for experimenting with memory.

This is a commemorative token, for the participation of the "savedScapes" project (https://www.fxhash.xyz/generative/16116) in the NFT SHOW EUROPE 2022 on the weekend of 17th and 18th September 2022.

As a thank you for all your support, "savedScapes" holders will have the right to mint the same number of editions for free.

The print with all holders will be done tomorrow (September 18th) at 10:00 BRT | 13:00 UTC | 15:00 CEST, and the token will open for collection after one hour at 11:00 am BRT | 14:00 UTC | 16:00 CEST.

Nothing is just one thing.

Generative Token by of Morbeck for fxhash

september 17, 2022

metadata.name: life is a (beautiful) mess #36
metadata.description:
when carefully applied, chaos brings things to life.

'life is a (beautiful) mess' was created as i led a certain amount of chaos take control of an animated textile algorithm i'm developing. 
as soon as it happened i realized that it was a great representation of our lives. 
each line represents one of us and the patterns that appear repeatedly are the situations we live which make us move, feel and be in a certain way. 
the image created is the sum of our paths in this life, as they only make sense when we look at them as one.

---

i hope you find it pleasant to watch this animation, how it develops and grows during aprox 1'30"
there are pieces drawn with the 4 typical school pen colors: black, green, blue and red. also a multicolor and a rare dark mode features.


press [s] to capture an image .png
press [r] to reload the animation
click the mouse to stop the animation
doubleclick the mouse to resume the animation

generative art created by mehno using p5js

metadata.name: Unstable Anticipation #66
metadata.description:
Minimal poster prints of blocks in motion.

Varying block arrangements fall from the canvas's top and interact with pegs near the bottom. After the animation completes, the scene is redrawn with a halftone pattern.

Matter JS is used to calculate the physics.

Viewing in desktop Chrome is recommended for the best results.
Press ’s’ to save a screenshot. Image size is 2318x3000px

Features
* The length of the simulation
* Number, size, and position of the pegs
* Halftone grid size
* Varying amount of roughness for distorted halftone shapes
* Shape arrangement and composition
* 60/40% Color or monochrome

metadata.name: Hello World #231
metadata.description:
With this token, I am entering a new chapter in making generative art. 

I recorded myself saying "Hello World" and converted the sound file to a set of amplitudes extracted from my voice. That set of amplitudes was then used to create a rotating set of discs that are orbiting a "Sun". 

As the system is rotating, the details of a generative overlay can be seen more clearly. This overlay is also a sneak peak into my next artwork coming soon.

Press keys 1-4 to change the view, press "F" to toggle framerate between 60 and 30.

metadata.name: Kings of Babylon #105
metadata.description:
Excavate Kings from the past.
Some are born first, and some are born later.
The long-dead are no longer breathless.
The new kings hail from distant dimensions.
Hunt their crowns, peel their eyes and savor in their glory.

25 Backgrounds
7 Forms
8 Mouths
26 Crowns
12 Eyes

Every Friday for 6 weeks, 2 Kings will be animated and airdropped to the holder, chosen through raffle ritual.
Check @syamarahakim and @spirouzi for the ritual.

metadata.name: Echoes of the Big Bang #126
metadata.description:
BIG BANG – A square shatters.
Tens of thousands pieces are hurled in all directions – SNAPSHOT.

Shattered according to the rules of the golden ratio.
Shift based on the Fibonacci numbers.

--
Keyboard control: Press "1" -> "5", saving the image in low -> high resolution. (It may take a while for the image to be generated in high resolution)
